 stronger reduced baseline using an effective-point or reduced-compartment model with explicit synaptic integration current or explicit delay structure\\ndocs/milestones.md:151: In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\\ndocs/milestones.md:153:**What should the wave model do differently than a baseline point-neuron model?**  \\ndocs/milestones.md:157: A geometry-sensitive shared-output effect, preferably on null-direction suppression or response latency, that survives a stronger reduced baseline.\\ndocs/milestones.md:160: The same stimulus driving the same circuit in two models, producing a small but real output difference that shrinks or disappears when geometry is shuffled.\\ndocs/milestones.md:174:* **Very strong:** the effect survives the stronger reduced baseline `P1`\\ndocs/milestones.md:179:2. **`10–25 s`**: split screen with matched point baseline on the left and surface model on the right for the same T4/T5-centered circuit  \\ndocs/milestones.md:186:* stimulus overview for the simple moving-edge input  \\ndocs/milestones.md:187:* split view showing baseline scalar activity versus surface-state activity on morphology  \\ndocs/milestones.md:188:* shared output trace overlay for the same circuit and stimulus  \\ndocs/milestones.md:192:* `P0` versus `P1` challenge-baseline comparison plot  \\ndocs/milestones.md:208:* creating the experiment manifest schema  \\ndocs/milestones.md:229:* `P0` and `P1` baseline definitions are explicit  \\ndocs/milestones.md:242:3. survival against a stronger reduced baseline  \\ndocs/milestones.md:271:Only the columns inside the selected stimulus footprint should be included, plus a **one-ring halo** so each active detector retains its local sampling neighborhood.\\ndocs/milestones.md:329:* root ID manifests for active, candidate, and context graphs  \\ndocs/milestones.md:341:* there is a named manifest for the locked boundary  \\ndocs/milestones.md:381:- manifest validation  \\ndocs/milestones.md:386:- flagging missing metadata needed for later coupling/model design\\ndocs/milestones.md:392:- the same experiment can be reproduced from a manifest\\ndocs/milestones.md:424:- exporting manifests and reports\\ndocs/milestones.md:435:- each subset produces a manifest and stats file  \\ndocs/milestones.md:527:## Milestone 7 — Map synapses and define inter-neuron coupling\\ndocs/milestones.md:540:- whether coupling is:  \\ndocs/milestones.md:552:- serializing coupling maps  \\ndocs/milestones.md:553:- coupling inspection tools\\ndocs/milestones.md:557:- defining coupling kernels  \\ndocs/milestones.md:560:- determining whether coupling is instantaneous, filtered, nonlinear, etc.\\ndocs/milestones.md:566:- coupling rules are configurable and versioned\\ndocs/milestones.md:574:### Milestone 8A — Canonical stimulus library\\ndocs/milestones.md:591:- stimulus generation code  \\ndocs/milestones.md:592:- parameterized stimulus configs  \\ndocs/milestones.md:598:- making sure the stimulus set is scientifically meaningful  \\ndocs/milestones.md:678:## Milestone 9 — Build the baseline non-wave simulator\\ndocs/milestones.md:691:- `baseline`  \\ndocs/milestones.md:692:- `surface_wave`\\ndocs/milestones.md:705:- defining a fair baseline model  \\ndocs/milestones.md:706:- making sure the baseline is not a strawman  \\ndocs/milestones.md:711:- the same experiment manifest runs in baseline mode  \\ndocs/milestones.md:791:- routing between coupling modes\\ndocs/milestones.md:847:- baseline vs wave comparisons are quantitative, not just visual\\ndocs/milestones.md:887:- reproducible differences between baseline and wave mode  \\ndocs/milestones.md:934:- baseline vs wave comparison mode  \\ndocs/milestones.md:969:- coupling mode  \\ndocs/milestones.md:978:- no lateral coupling  \\ndocs/milestones.md:1000: